title: Florida Democratic Party
deleted: In the [[Florida gubernatorial election, 2006|2006 election]], the Democratic nominee for governor was U.S. Representative [[Jim Davis (Florida politician)|Jim Davis]] from [[Tampa, Florida]]. He lost the election to Florida Attorney General [[Charlie Crist]].

The most Democratic region of the state is [[South Florida]], which contains the large cities of [[Miami, Florida|Miami]], [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], and [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]]. The Tampa Bay region is also relatively Democratic, although it has become much more competitive in recent electoral cycles. [[Leon County, Florida|Leon County]], which contains the state capitol of [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]] and [[Florida State University]], and [[Alachua County]], home to the city of [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and the [[University of Florida]], are also strong Democratic areas. North Florida and the panhandle are also very Democratic on the local level, although those two regions are solid Republican strongholds in presidential elections.

Florida Democrats demanded, on March 13, 2008, a new primary vote, and state party officials had a proposal for recouping the 210 delegates the Sunshine State lost when it moved its primary ahead of the approved time frame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/03/13/primary.proposal.intl/index.html |title=Florida Dems devise plan for new primary - CNN.com |website=edition.cnn.com |access-date=2016-06-12}}</ref> After weeks of negotiations, the Florida Democratic Party said on March 17, 2008, that it would not hold [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|a second primary]] in the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/03/17/florida.primary.decision/index.html |title=No new primary for Florida Democrats - CNN.com |website=edition.cnn.com |access-date=2016-06-12}}</ref>
